    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Shell tall and conical (‘cap-shaped’), oval in outline, the aperture covering the full surface area. Apex recurved and strongly displaced to the anterior end. Outer surface of shell sculptured by about 26 distinctive radiating ribs, each bearing numerous small, sharp prickles (can be partially eroded in older specimens). Shell colour brown with black ribs and black interior.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_2816",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Shell up to 30 mm in length.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_2817",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Namibia and South Africa<i>.</i></p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Namibia to KwaZulu-Natal south coast.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_2818",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Occupies a distinct habitat concealed in rock crevices or under rocks in mid- to high intertidal zone, but can be abundant in such sites.</p><p>Grazers, scraping algae and lichens off the rocks with a powerful radula.</p><p>Growth rate about 5-6 mm per year and maximum age about 5-6 years.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_2819",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Herbivorous, feeding on algae.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_2820",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>A protandrous hermaphrodite, males becoming mature at an age of about one year and size of about 10-12 mm shell length and then changing sex into females at an age of two years and shell length of about 16 mm. The resulting sex ratio in the population is about two males to one female. Spawning takes place mostly in summer (Nov/Dec) with a second smaller spawning in Autumn (April) and the larvae develop in the plankton.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_2821",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The prickly ribs in the shell are very distinctive and make it unlikely that this species will be confused with others, although two other smooth-shelled species of <i>Helcion </i>co-occur on rocky shores in the region.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_2822",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fifth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 170).<br><br>Gray, DR & Hodgson, AN (2003). Growth and reproduction in the high-shore South African limpet <i>Helcion pectunculus</i> (Mollusca: Patellogastropoda). <i>African Zoology</i>, 38(2), 371-386.<br><br>Kilburn, R & Rippey, E (1982). Sea Shells of Southern Africa. Macmillan South Africa, Johannesburg (p. 37).",
